// Provide a fix for the buggy function.
Root cause: The root cause of the bug is that the function does not properly handle the case when the lower limit is greater than the length of the string. In this case, the function tries to access an index of the string that is out of range, resulting in a `StringIndexOutOfBoundsException`. This is because the function does not check if the lower limit is greater than the length of the string before trying to access the string at that index.
Suggestion: Check Lower Limit Before Accessing String
One potential fix is to add a check before accessing the string at the lower limit index. We can add a simple if statement to check if the lower limit is greater than the length of the string, and if so, return the original string or an empty string, depending on the desired behavior. This would prevent the `StringIndexOutOfBoundsException` from being thrown. The modified code would be:
```java
if (lower > str.length()) {
    return str;
}
```
This fix is simple and effective, but it may not be the desired behavior in all cases.
// Buggy Function
public static String abbreviate(String str, int lower, int upper, String appendToEnd) {
    // initial parameter checks
    if (str == null) {
        return null;
    }
    if (str.length() == 0) {
        return StringUtils.EMPTY;
    }

    // if the lower value is greater than the length of the string,
    // set to the length of the string
    // if the upper value is -1 (i.e. no limit) or is greater
    // than the length of the string, set to the length of the string
    if (upper == -1 || upper > str.length()) {
        upper = str.length();
    }
    // if upper is less than lower, raise it to lower
    if (upper < lower) {
        upper = lower;
    }

    StringBuffer result = new StringBuffer();
    int index = StringUtils.indexOf(str, " ", lower);
    if (index == -1) {
        result.append(str.substring(0, upper));
        // only if abbreviation has occured do we append the appendToEnd value
        if (upper != str.length()) {
            result.append(StringUtils.defaultString(appendToEnd));
        }
    } else if (index > upper) {
        result.append(str.substring(0, upper));
        result.append(StringUtils.defaultString(appendToEnd));
    } else {
        result.append(str.substring(0, index));
        result.append(StringUtils.defaultString(appendToEnd));
    }
    return result.toString();
}
// Fixed Function

